`` rm -rf ~/.bittensor/bittensor/``

getting multi gpu devices (8-10x) and using multi-gpu reg can make the process easier. Generally speaking, not saying one should go THAT crazy on reg. If multiple addresses began doing what that address is doing (adding multiple of 150 gpus) difficulty would jump much...... 2-3 weeks ago the team said the entire network has ~550 3090 equivalents registering at any time...... so 150 would be a big chunk of it.... can also see it doesn't take many 150s to go far above 550..... this is how difficulty is now 5-25 times higher than when i started 2 months ago.... the additional compute is hopefully added by many not just 2-3 folks each adding GPUs numbering in 100s.

the spend on renting GPUs numbering above 100 is tens of dollars per hour. 

reasonably many individuals and even more companies can afford that....

the nice thing about the protective mechanism of the registration process is that if entity X doesn't mind spending $1000/hr on registration, it doesn't mean they would register many keys super fast -- difficulty jumps up to keep the rate of key turn-over constant.
the not-as-nice part is that it is possible to take over a large percentage of the network with sustained compute at a high level over time.... given the keys can be kept.

theoretically, there is no mechanism stopping an entity from taking this to the extreme -- above 50% of nodes... but again, has to be over time. However this is the nature of these systems.... at some point the network will be too large for such a possibility to be realistic.
